Problem Set 2: What determines wages?

What factors determine a persons wage is of just importance for policy. Today we are do some simple analyses using a dataset on individual characteristics and wage outcomes in 1980. You can find the CVS dataset under data in Canvas (Wages).

3. Regression 1 (Hours and IQ)

Run a regression with hours and IQ scoreas the explanatory variables. What are the coefficients for both and their interpretation (remember to include whether they are statistically significant).

fit1 <- lm(wage~hours+IQ, wages)
summary(fit1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wage ~ hours + IQ, data = wages)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -905.00 -254.76  -51.02  201.75 2013.33 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  226.752    137.956   1.644    0.101    
## hours         -2.662      2.102  -1.266    0.206    
## IQ             8.577      1.025   8.371 3.43e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 386.9 on 660 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.09703,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.09429 
## F-statistic: 35.46 on 2 and 660 DF,  p-value: 2.358e-15
plot_coeffs(fit1)

This means that if hours differed by one unit, wage will differ by -2.6619513 units, on average, while holding IQ constant.

This means that if IQ differed by one unit, wage will differ by 8.5773174 units, on average, while holding hours constant. This is statistically significant at the 0.001 percent level.

We would expect an average monthly earning (wage) to be 226.7522724

hours is not statistically significant since p-value is 0.21

IQ is statistically significant since p-value is 0

The model is signficant

The Adjusted R2 value is 0.0943. This tells us that 9.43% of the variation in monthly earnings, as quantified by wage, is reduced by taking into account hours and IQ.

8. F-test

What does the F-test tell you about the model in Q6? What about the R2 and adjusted R2?

The model is significant

The R2 value is 0.1736. The Adjusted R2 value is 0.166. This tells us that 16.6% of the variation in monthly earnings, as quantified by wage, is reduced by taking into account hours, IQ, educ, age, exper, and tenure.

9. Drop tenure and hours

Can we drop tenure and hours? (Do a joint test). What are the results and how do we interpret them?

Both tenure and hours are not significant, therefore can be removed. The joint test fails to reject the null hypothesis that tenure = hours = 0.
